\"stopReason\": \"stop\", \"timestamp\": 1782621906894}}\n[assistant-event] thinking_start\n[thinking] **Evaluating inner classes in Scala**\n[thinking] \n[thinking] I'm considering that a local anonymous class with EnclosingMethod should indeed return a class. Scala likely emits EnclosingMethod for an anonymous inner class in a method. So, there might be a chance for our private nested class to avoid having an enclosing instance. Maybe I could add a local class that has a private constructor to avoid that risk? It's worth exploring more options here!\n[thinking] \n[thinking] **Exploring class structure**\n[thinking] \n[thinking] I'm considering using a non-static member inner class with a private constructor. I wonder if it would really fail? It seems like the compiler might say there’s no declared constructor with empty parameters, but rather one with an enclosing class parameter. If the class is nested inside a test class instead of being an object, would that allow for a private constructor and a factory method in the companion object? I'm curious about whether it could work out!\n[thinking] \n[thinking] **Evaluating test class structure**\n[thinking] \n[thinking] I'm noticing that the top-level test class isn't recognized as a test class. That seems like a potential issue, especially since the naming convention for inner or anonymous classes doesn't allow the \"$\" character. I found that the file or class AbstractPropsTest doesn't include a \"$\". So, it looks like I've reached a final conclusion here about the test class structure needing some adjustments to comply with naming conventions.\n[thinking] \n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[assistant-event] text_start\n[assistant] Implemented coverage-focused test for `org.apache.pekko.actor.AbstractProps`.\n[assistant] \n[assistant] Changed:\n[assistant] - Added `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.6.0/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_actor_2_13/AbstractPropsTest.scala`\n[assistant] \n[assistant] T